1210","1121":"1121","1176":"1176","before 1150":"before 1150","1150":"1150","Coughton, Alcester, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England",",,, England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cocton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire): habitational name from any of various places called Colton in England. Examples in Norfolk, Staffordshire, and North Yorkshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (or the cognate Old Norse <i>Koli</i>; see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The place so named in Somerset has as its first element the Old English personal name <i>Cūla</i> (of uncertain origin). The one in Cumbria has a river name apparently derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘hazel’. This English name is also common in Ireland; it was the name of a bishop of Derry in 1397. There seems also to have been confusion with   Culliton  .","Scottish and Irish (Monaghan): shortened and altered form of Gaelic <b>Mac Haldan</b>, ‘son of <i>Haldan</i>’, see   Haldane  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Culton","meanings":["Scottish (Kirkcudbrightshire): variant of   Colton   or   Culliton  ."]},{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Colten","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Colton  ."]},{"name":"Coulton","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Colton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Cocton was born about 1150, in Coughton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of William FitzRANULF de COCTON and Mrs William FitzRANULF de COCTON. He had at least 1 son with Mrs William De Cocton. He died in 1259, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 110."},"et":{"about 1150–1259":"umbes 1150–1259","1150–1259":"1150–1259","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1121–Female":"1121–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1259":"1259","1210":"1210","1121":"1121","1176":"1176","before 1150":"enne 1150","1150":"1150","Coughton, Alcester, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1150–1259":"noin 1150–1259","1150–1259":"1150–1259","1176–Female":"1176–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1121–Female":"1121–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","1259":"1259","1210":"1210","1121":"1121","1176":"1176","before 1150":"ennen vuotta 1150","1150":"1150","Coughton, Alcester, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1150–1259":"environ 1150–1259","1150–1259":"1150–1259","1176–Female":"1176–Décédée","1210–Male":"1210–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1121–Female":"1121–Décédée","about 1150":"environ 1150","1259":"1259","1210":"1210","1121":"1121","1176":"1176","before 1150":"avant 1150","1150":"1150","Coughton, Alcester, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Warwickshire, Engla